04627nam a22005655i 9780774854498DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991976xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748544987 a10.59962/97807748544982doi  a(DE-B1597)661861  a(OCoLC)816857672  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1089.O5.A44 1976eb 7aBIO0230002bisacsh04a971.11 aOrmsby, Margaret A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Pioneer Gentlewoman in British Columbia :bThe Recollections of Susan Allison /cMargaret A. Ormsby. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1976  a1 online resource (205 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Pioneers of British Columbia00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPhotographic Credits -- tIntroduction -- tSome Recollections of A Pioneer of the Sixties -- tSome Recollections of A Pioneer of the Seventies -- tMemoirs of A Pioneer of the Eighties -- tWhen the River Rose* -- tAccount of the Similkameen Indians of British Columbia* -- tThe Big Men of the Mountains -- tThe Glittering Hair -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex -- tThe Pioneers of British Columbia0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a'My husband, alarmed, left me and ran to the Indian ranch returning with one of Quinisco's sisters . She smoothed up my bed and suggested "whiskey" which I swallowed. I think I would have swallowed anything to get rid of the pain. About nine o'clock next day my baby was born two months too soon, the first white child born in the Similkameen Valley.' In 1860, at the age of fourteen, Susan Louisa Moir left England for British Columbia. After settling initially at Hope, she lived briefly in both Victoria and New Westminster, then B.C.'s two most important settlements. Returning to Hope, she helped her mother open the community's first school, and in 1868 she married John Fall Allison, riding on her honeymoon over the Allison Trail into the unsettled Similkameen Valley. Her record of the voyage, of Victoria, New Westminster, and Hope as they were in the 1860s, and her memories of the isolated but fulfilling life she, her husband, and their fourteen children led in the Similkameen and Okanagan Valleys provide a unique view of the pioneer mind and spirit. There were exciting moments -- a horseback journey to Hope through a forest fire that made the Skagit River boil, her husband's boat nearly crushed by a gigantic ice floe on Lake Okanagan -- but setting the tone of the whole account is an abiding natural curiosity and respect for both of her closest neighbours -- the Similkameen and Okanagan Indians and the wilderness itself. It is these qualities, expressed in forceful, uncomplicated prose, that make Susan Allison's Recollections a major addition to Canadian pioneer literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezOkanagan River Valley (B.C. and Wash.). 0aPioneerszOkanagan River Valley (B.C. and Wash.)vBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Adventurers & Explorers.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485449840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774854498423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774854498/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141940-4  Un